%
CAP Theorem (Brewer's Theorem): it is impossible for a distributed computer system to simultaneously provide Consistency (all nodes see the same data at the same time), Availability (a guarantee that every request receives a response about whether it was successful or failed) and Partition tolerance (the system continues to operate despite arbitrary message loss or failure of part of the system) - Eric Brewer, Symposium on Principles of Distributed Computing (PODC) (2000)
%
CAP Theorem (Brewer's Theorem) - Clarification 1: Because Partitions are rare, there is little reason to forfeit Consistency or Availability when the system is not partitioned. - Eric Brewer, IEEE Computer Society 'Computer' Magazine (2012)
%
CAP Theorem (Brewer's Theorem) - Clarification 2: The choice between Consistency and Availability can occur many times within the same system at very fine granularity; not only can subsystems make different choices, but the choice can change according to the operation or even the specific data or user involved. - Eric Brewer, IEEE Computer Society 'Computer' Magazine (2012)
%
CAP Theorem (Brewer's Theorem) - Clarification 3: All three properties (Consistency, Availability, Partition tolerance) are more continuous than binary. Availability is obviously continuous from 0 to 100 percent, but there are also many levels of Consistency, and even Partitions have nuances, including disagreement within the system about whether a Partition exists. - Eric Brewer, IEEE Computer Society 'Computer' Magazine (2012)
%
Adding manpower to a late software project makes it later. Nine women can't make a baby in one month. - Fred Brooks, 'The Mythical Man-Month' (1975)
%
Classen's Law: Usefulness = log(Technology) - Theo A. C. M. Claasen, CTO of Philips Semiconductors (1999)
%
Conway's Law: Organizations which design systems are constrained to produce designs which are copies of the communication structures of these organizations. - Melvin Conway, 'National Symposium on Modular Programming', 1968
%
The organization of the software and the organization of the software team will be congruent. - Eric S. Raymond, paraphrasing Conway's Law in 'The New Hacker's Dictionary'
%
If the parts of an organization (e.g. teams, departments, or subdivisions) do not closely reflect the essential parts of the product, or if the relationship between organizations do not reflect the relationships between product parts, then the project will be in trouble... therefore: Make sure the organization is compatible with the product architecture. - James O. Coplien and Neil B. Harrison, paraphasing Conway's Law (2004)
%
Ducharm's Axiom: If you view your problem closely enough you will recognize yourself as part of the problem.
%
Dykstra's Observation: If debugging is the process of removing bugs, then programming must be the process of putting them in.
